trans-unit.source: One detail we didn’t discuss in the “References and Borrowing” section in Chapter 4 is that every reference in Rust has a lifetime, which is the scope for which that reference is valid. Most of the time, lifetimes are implicit and inferred, just like most of the time, types are inferred. We must annotate types when multiple types are possible. In a similar way, we must annotate lifetimes when the lifetimes of references could be related in a few different ways. Rust requires us to annotate the relationships using generic lifetime parameters to ensure the actual references used at runtime will definitely be valid.

trans-unit.source: Patterns come in two forms: refutable and irrefutable. Patterns that will match for any possible value passed are irrefutable. An example would be x in the statement let x = 5; because x matches anything and therefore cannot fail to match. Patterns that can fail to match for some possible value are refutable. An example would be Some(x) in the expression if let Some(x) = a_value because if the value in the a_value variable is None rather than Some, the Some(x) pattern will not match.
trans-unit.target: 패턴은 반박과 반박의 두 가지 형태로 제공됩니다. 전달 된 가능한 값과 일치하는 패턴은 반박 할 수 없습니다 . 예는 것 x 문에 let x = 5; 때문에 x 는 모든 항목과 일치하므로 일치하지 않을 수 없습니다. 일부 가능한 값과 일치하지 않는 패턴은 반박 할 수 있습니다 . 예로들 수 Some(x) 식의 if let Some(x) = a_value 의 값 경우 때문에 a_value 변수가없는 None 아닌 Some 의 Some(x) 패턴이 일치하지 않습니다.
